dataElements.name: VL_LAB_HIVstatus_Type
dataElements.description:
The number of confirmed VL cases disaggregated by patient type and HIV status.
HIV status: 
- HIV positive : Tested positve for HIV, or self reported
- HIV negative : Tested negative for HIV
- HIV status unknown : not tested for HIV 
Patient type: see VL_EPI_Type for definition

A case of coinfection is an HIV-positive person showing clinical signs of any form of visceral leishmaniasis, with serological and/or parasitological confirmation of the diagnosis. All VL-confirmed cases should be tested for HIV.

The sum of the number of cases in each category should be equal to the total number of VL cases.
dataElements.formName: Number of VL cases, by HIV status and patient type

dataElements.name: VL_GEN_Def_Relapse
dataElements.description: Please enter the definition of relapse for VL that is used in your country. If there is no established definition, please enter 'No definition available'.
dataElements.formName: How do you define relapse for VL?

dataElements.name: VL_EPI_Type
dataElements.description:
The number of confirmed VL cases disaggregated by patient type. 
Patient type:
- New case: a patient who has never been diagnosed for VL (clinically or with lab confirmation).
- Relapse: a patient who experiences recurrence of VL symptoms with parasitological confirmation at any time point after initial cure.
- Unspecified: Please use this category if the type of patient is unknown or not recorded.

The sum of the number of cases in each category should be equal to the total number of VL cases.
dataElements.formName: Number of VL cases, by patient type

dataElements.name: PKDL_LAB_HIV
dataElements.description: The number of probable PKDL coinfected with HIV. A case of coinfection is an HIV-positive person showing clinical signs of PKDL with serological and/or parasitological confirmation of the diagnosis.
dataElements.formName: Number of probable PKDL cases coinfected with HIV

dataElements.name: VL_LAB_RDT_results_type
dataElements.shortName: VL suspects by Rapid Test result
dataElements.description:
The number of suspected VL cases tested with RDT, disaggregated by patient type (new and unspecified only) and RDT result. 
Results:
- Positive RDT 
- Negative RDT
- Inconclusive RDT 
Patient type: see VL_EPI_Type for definition

The sum of the number of cases in each category should be equal to the total number of probable cases tested with RDT.
dataElements.formName: Number of VL suspects tested with Rapid Diagnostic Tests, by test result

dataElements.name: VL_TREAT_AE
dataElements.description:
The number of confirmed VL cases having presented a severe or life-threatening adverse event, disaggregated by patient type.
Severe or life-threatening adverse event are defined as any event classified as severe (grade 3 in CTCAE) or life threatening (grade 4). 
The reporting of severe adverse events is independent from other outcome reporting at the end of the treatment.
Please refer to the following document for more information: Common terminology criteria for adverse events (CTCAE). https://evs.nci.nih.gov/ftp1/CTCAE/CTCAE_4.03/CTCAE_4.03_2010-06-14_QuickReference_5x7.pdf

Patient type: See VL_EPI_Type for definition

Minor adverse events are not included in severe adverse event reporting.
dataElements.formName: Number of VL cases with a severe or life-threatening adverse event, by patient type

dataElements.name: VL_LAB_clinical
dataElements.description:
The number of VL cases that are clinically confirmed disaggregated by patient type. 
Clinically-confirmed VL case: A probable VL case that has not been confirmed by any laboratory test (i.e. test(s) not done or negative), but is assessed by a clinician to be a confirmed VL case based on clinical grounds.
These confirmed cases should have their information collected on a patient form, and recorded on the register. They should be treated as per the clinical guidelines.
Patient type: see VL_EPI_Type for definition
dataElements.formName: Number of VL cases clinically confirmed, by patient type

dataElements.name: VL_GEN_EPID_new focus
dataElements.description:
Please specify the number of new VL foci reported in your country in the reporting year. 

A focus is a defined and circumscribed geographical implementation unit (region, district, village) containing the epidemiological factors needed for transmission, i.e.:
-a human community
-a source of infection
-a competent vector population, and
-appropriate environmental conditions

In practice for surveillance purposes, a focus is a defined and circumscribed geographical implementation unit where there is evidence that locally acquired confirmed cases have been reported even if the transmission cycle has not been described. 

A new focus is defined as a focus where leishmaniasis transmission was never reported previously.
dataElements.formName: How many new foci of visceral leishmaniasis (VL) have been detected in the reporting year?

dataElements.name: VL_GEN_EPID_outbreak
dataElements.description:
Please specify if there were any outbreaks of VL reported in your country in the reporting year. 

WHO defines a disease outbreak as the occurrence of cases of disease in excess of what would normally be expected in a defined community, geographical area or season. An outbreak may occur in a restricted geographical area or may extend over several countries. It may last for a few days or weeks, or for several years. 

A single case of a communicable disease long absent from a population, or caused by an agent not previously recognized in that community or area, or the emergence of a previously unknown disease, may also constitute an outbreak and should be reported and investigated.
dataElements.formName: Were there any visceral leishmaniasis (VL) outbreaks over the reporting year?

The sum of the number of deaths in each category should be equal to the total number of deaths among VL cases.

dataElements.name: VL_Monthly _File
dataElements.description:
Please upload the excel file with the number of confirmed VL cases disaggregated by month and by the smallest administrative level available (ideally administrative level 3). 
Administrative level refers to the probable place of infection. If information is only available on the place of treatment, please indicate this clearly on the first tab of the file using the dropdown menu. 

Please also indicate if the implementation unit is considered endemic or non-endemic.  
Endemicity of a given area: evidence of ongoing transmission based on ?1 locally acquired confirmed case per year in a defined area, for the previous 10 years.
A country/region/district ceases to be designated endemic when there are 0 locally acquired cases per year in the defined area for the previous 10 years, despite proven surveillance and active case finding.

The number of VL cases followed-up 6 months after treatment completion, disaggregated by patient type and final treatment outcome. 
Final treatment outcome is evaluated six months after treatment has been completed
- Final cure: an initially cured patient who remains symptom-free six months after the end of treatment.
- Relapse: any reappearance of VL symptoms within a period of six months after the end of treatment. Please note that relapses may occur more than 6 months after treatment completion
- Death: any death, whether or not related to VL.

Patient type: see VL_EPI_Type for definition
The sum of the number of cases in each category should be equal to the total number of VL cases followed-up at 6 months.

- Defaulter: the patient is known by the clinician not to have completed the treatment, and does not come back for assessment 
- Unknown: the status of treatment completion is unknown/unrecorded 
Patient type: see VL_EPI_Type for definition

At initial assessment (at the last day of drug treatment), WHO defines treatment outcome as:

- Death: any death occurring anytime up to the initial assessment, whether or not related to VL.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                           - Unknown: the patient has not been assesed by a clinician following treatment, or the result has not been recorded.

1. EPIDEMIOLOGY

Case definitions

Probable VL case: WHO defines a probable case of visceral leishmaniasis (or Kala-azar) as a person living in or having travelled to endemic areas showing clinical signs of VL (mainly irregular fever lasting more than two weeks, splenomegaly and/or weight loss).

Confirmed VL cases

  • Laboratory-Confirmed VL case: A probable VL case with laboratory confirmation, either serological (RDT, DAT, ELISA, IFAT)  and/or parasitological (smear, culture) and/or positive PCR and related techniques. 
  • OR Clinically-Confirmed VL case: A probable VL case which has not been confirmed by laboratory (test not done or negative), but the clinician decides on clinical grounds that the case is clinically confirmed.

1.1 Confirmed VL Cases (either laboratory or clinically), by Type

Relapse: WHO defines a relapse as a VL case who experiences recurrence of VL symptoms with parasitological confirmation at any time point after initial cure.

4.2 Initial treatment outcome by treatment regimen

At initial assessment (at the last day of drug treatment), WHO defines as:

  • Initial cure: a full course of drugs has been completed AND the patient has clinically improved. Clinical criteria for cure should be assessed as no fever + regression of enlarged spleen + return of appetite and/or gain in body weight.
  • Failure/Non-response: signs and symptoms persist or recur. Switch to a second-line drug because of no response to the first-line drug.
  • Death: any death occurring anytime up to the initial assessment, whether or not related to VL.
  • Unknown: the patient has not been assessed by a clinician following his treatment, or the result has not been recorded.

• Death: any death, whether or not related to VL.

PKDL

Probable PKDL: WHO defines a probable PKDL case as a patient from a L. donovani-endemic area who has a typically symmetrical macular, papular, nodular or mixed rash often starting on the face with further spread to other parts of the body without loss of sensation and positive rk39 RDT- that may occasionally present even in the absence of a previous history of visceral leishmaniasis.

Confirmed PKDL: WHO defines a confirmed PKDL case as a probable PKDL case with Leishmania infection confirmed by PCR or a slit-skin smear or biopsy.
